      <div xml:id="NA143-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">maṉaimaruṭci. (G1+2: 1. itu makaṭ pōkkiya tāy kūṟiyatu. 2. maṉaimaruṭciyumām.)</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Confusion in the house. (G1+2: 1. This is what the mother said who had had [her] daughter go. 2. Confusion in the house.)</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA143">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            aitē kamma yāṉē yoyyeṉat</l>
<l>            tarumaṇaṉ ñemiriya tirunakar muṟṟat</l>
<l>            tōrai yāyamu nocciyuṅ kāṇṭoṟu</l>
<l>            nīrvār kaṇṇeṉ kaliḻu meṉṉiṉuṅ</l>
<l>            kiḷḷaiyuṅ kiḷaiyeṉak kūu miḷaiyōḷ </l>
<l>            vaḻuvila ḷamma tāṉē kuḻīi</l>
<l>            yampaṉ mūtū ralarvāyp peṇṭi</l>
<l>            riṉṉā viṉṉurai kēṭṭa ciṉṉā</l>
<l>            ḷaṟiyēṉ pōla vuyirē</l>
<l>            ṉaṟiya nāṟuniṉ katuppeṉ ṟēṉē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Beautiful, go<note place="foot">The imperative <term xml:lang="ta">ēku</term> refers to the fact that the girl has already gone with her lover, and the speaker (mother or foster-mother) has no intention to stop her, accepting a fait accompli.</note>, alas, [is] it.</l>
<l rend="indent4">I, oy<note place="foot">How to connect and how to interpret <term xml:lang="ta">oyyeṉa</term>?</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent">even more than me who weeps, me, eyes overflowing with water</l>
<l rend="indent2">whenever I see the Nocci tree and [her] playmates</l>
<l rend="indent2">in the courtyard of the brilliant mansion, spread with sea-given sand,</l>
<l>she herself is without fault, alas,</l>
<l rend="indent3">the young one who crows intimately(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kiḷai eṉa kūum</term>: she talks with the parakeet as if it were her relative?</note> even to the parakeet,</l>
<l>– I who said 'fragrant is your fragrant hair'<note place="foot">Either <term xml:lang="ta">naṟiya</term> has to be read as predicate noun n.pl., or <term xml:lang="ta">nāṟum</term> as finite verb n.sg. plus <term xml:lang="ta">naṟiya</term> as adverb. In any case the point seems to be a lot of fragrance.</note>,</l>
<l>I who did not sigh, as if I didn't know,</l>
<l rend="indent">for the few days that I heard the unpleasant pleasing talk</l>
<l rend="indent2">of gossip-mouthed women in the old village [full of] rumours,</l>
<l rend="indent3">crowding together.</l>
        </lg>
